<DOC><DOCNO> AP890924-0018 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1212EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Teachers     09-24 0263</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Korea-Teachers,0270</SECOND><HEAD>Teachers, Students Demonstrate to Protest Ban on Union</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thousands of teachers, students andtheir supporters demonstrated in eight cities across the countrySunday to protest a ban on a teachers' union.   About 1,500 students hurled rocks and bottles at riot police indowntown Seoul after they were blocked from entering YonseiUniversity. No injuries were reported immediately, but policedetained dozens of protesters in Seoul.   ``Down with (President) Roh Tae-woo,'' the protesters shouted aspolice firing tear gas chased them into alleys and side streets.   About 1,000 teachers, students and workers held a separateanti-government rally after staying overnight inside the campus,which has been sealed off by thousands of riot police.   Police also reported scattered rallies in seven other cities. Inthe southern opposition stronghold of Kwangju, about 3,000 teachersand supporters demonstrated on a university campus, news reportssaid.   Education authorities have outlawed the National Teachers Unionand ordered teachers punished for union activity, contendingleftists were using the union to spread revolutionary ideas amongstudents.   Union leaders claim education in South Korea has been used bydictators to cement their power and have called for educationalreforms.   They say more than 1,500 teachers have been forced out of theirjobs since about 20,000 of South Korea's 300,000 primary andsecondary school teachers tried to organize a nationwide unionearly this year.   Thousands of teachers have defected from the union. But unionleaders claim about 8,000 still are with the movement, which hasbeen supported by dissidents, radical students and other laborgroups.</TEXT></DOC>